{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[5, 6]", "headings": "['4.0.2. Higher Dimension Evaluation']"}, "page_content": "4.0.2. Higher Dimension Evaluation\nFollowing Garrido et al. (2020) and Borysov et al. (2019), we compare the categorical partial joint distribution of synthetic populations generated by WGAN-GP models. We used a standardized root mean square error (SRMSE) and coefficient of determination R 2 as metrics for evaluating multi-dimensional distributions. We employ distinct subsets\nof attributes to encompass diverse features of the joint distribution. The evaluation is done for the following k-joint of attributes, with total categories in brackets:\n- 210-dimensional joint of AGE(5), SEX(2) and BOST LAN(21).\n- 16k-dimensional joint of UP FORV(3), SUN2KN(7), SUN2KI(10), HHSTORL(6) and SNIKOD(13).\n- 7M-dimensional joint of AGE(5), SEX(2), BOST LAN(21), SUN2KI(10), SNIKOD(13), LIVSKAT(8), SUN2KN(7), and INKUP(5).", "type": "Document"}}